      <body>
         <listPerson>
            <person xml:id="pers0780">
               <p>A native of <placeName>Leeds</placeName>, trained as a paper maker and corn
                  miller, Garforth married <persName>Mary Sedgwick</persName> (<date from="1734"
                     to="1773">1734–73</date>) in <date when="1758">1758</date>. Shortly after he
                  partnered with his brother-in-law to set up the first mechanised cotton textile
                  factory in <placeName>Skipton</placeName> in <placeName>Craven,
                     Yorkshire</placeName>. <persName><ref target="/persons/pers2180.xml"
                     />JW</persName> preached outside his house on <date when="1766-07-25">July 25,
                     1766</date> (see <hi rend="italic">Journal, Works</hi>, 22:52, correcting fn
                  29). Successful in business, Garforth became a pillar of Methodism in his
                  community, hosting visiting preachers, providing support for poorer members of the
                  society, and funding the construction of a chapel there in <date when="1791"
                     >1791</date>. See <hi rend="italic">WHS</hi> 17 (<date>1930</date>): 184–87;
                  and W. Harbutt Dawson, <hi rend="italic">History of Skipton</hi>
                     (<placeName>London</placeName>: Simpkin, Marshall, and Co., <date when="1882"
                     >1882</date>), 304–06.</p>
            </person>
         </listPerson>
      </body>
   </text>
